Nine

A small language and compiler. You write .9 files, nine preprocesses them,
lexes, parses, emits assembly, calls clang, and gives you a binary.

Right now the backend that actually works is macOS arm64. x86_64 is stubbed.

Build

  cc build.c -o build
  ./build

That compiles the compiler and links ./nine. Re-run ./build when you change
src/*.c.

Run

  ./nine examples/000_helloworld.9 -r

  -o path     where the binary goes (default: ./basename of input)
  -s          keep the .s file (next to -o output, or in cwd)
  -r          run the binary after linking
  -t arm64    target (default arm64)
  -v          version

Early project. Expect things to move.
